This paper deals with object counting in images, which is a common problem in computer vision (CV). The proposed approach involves using a specific pooling technique in the backend of a convolutional neural network (CNN) to improve the generalization capability of the model. This technique is relevant to the subfield of CV that deals with CNNs and their architectures, which is covered by cs.CV. Additionally, the paper discusses the problem of overfitting, which is a common concern in machine learning (ML) and is covered by cs.LG. The proposed approach involves a linear mapping problem, which is a common topic in artificial intelligence (AI) and is covered by cs.AI. The paper also discusses the use of smaller-sized image patches, which is relevant to the subfield of multimedia (MM) and is covered by cs.MM. Finally, the paper proposes a new approach to object counting, which involves training a CNN, a topic that is relevant to the subfield of neural networks (NE) and is covered by cs.NE.
